{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"10ddbe3f-44b9-445f-b58c-7678ef8548fe","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the workloads you already have **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installs but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, you need `update`, not `repair`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, verify the MAUI workload is present with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5dff6363-19ac-46df-aceb-78dd70c98ce0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question—I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":248,"requestId":"9813:8E236:1581578:180AF7B:6A051DA0"},"id":"5e9c9110-bade-43b3-94b5-7d32eaf2eaf6","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:09.241Z","parentId":"ccaa0f90-3c7c-4c7a-bac5-4da13ec9e86f"}
